{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520609"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13231"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.42,0.15,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88496"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5665"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72699"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1939"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2576"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12749"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88496"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of fever, productive cough with blood-stained sputum, night sweats and fatigue. He works on a cattle station in the Northern Territory. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and chronic kidney disease. He is an ex-smoker with a 15 pack-year history. His regular medications include metformin and irbesartan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. There are coarse crackles in the right lower zone. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 18 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 20 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation without cavitation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcid-fast bacilli smear: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum culture: gram-negative bacteria isolated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bovine tuberculosis","Fungal pneumonia","Melioidosis","Legionnaires\u0027 disease","Klebsiella pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Emelioidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by the gram-negative bacterium \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E. The diagnosis is supported by several key features: residence in an endemic area (Northern Territory), occupational exposure to soil (working in agriculture), presence of major risk factors (diabetes and chronic kidney disease), acute pneumonia with systemic symptoms, and isolation of a gram-negative organism. \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E is resistant to cephalosporins. As a result carbapenems are recommended as empiric treatment in patients with community-acquired pneumonia who are at risk of infection with melioidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBovine tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more indolently and would be expected to show acid-fast bacilli on sputum smear. While zoonotic transmission is possible in cattle workers, human cases are extremely rare in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to grow as a gram-negative organism on culture. While the patient\u0027s diabetes puts him at risk, the acute presentation and positive gram-negative culture make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegionnaires\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in clusters associated with contaminated water systems rather than soil exposure. While it can present similarly, the epidemiological features and occupational exposure make melioidosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a community-acquired pneumonia in alcoholics or as a hospital-acquired infection. While it is a gram-negative organism that can cause severe pneumonia, the geographical and occupational context make melioidosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melioidosis should be suspected in patients from tropical regions who present with pneumonia and have risk factors including diabetes and soil exposure.","Burkholderia pseudomallei is a gram-negative bacterium resistant to cephalosporins, requiring empiric carbapenem therapy.","Key risk factors for melioidosis include diabetes, chronic kidney disease, and occupational exposure to soil or water in endemic areas."],"references":["Karunanayake P. Melioidosis: clinical aspects. Clin Med (Lond). 2022 Jan;22(1):6-8. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8813014/","Nguyen HVN, Smith ME, Hayoun MA. Glanders and Melioidosis. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2022 Sep 28]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448110/","Adigun R, Singh R. Tuberculosis. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 May 14]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441916/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72699"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72699"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-05T09:17:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-05T09:19:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5665"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88496"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"re